15:31.530 --> 15:34.266
>> Bill Whitaker: THIS PAST
WEEK, CALIFORNIA DECLARED A

15:34.333 --> 15:36.635
STATEWIDE DROUGHT EMERGENCY.

15:36.702 --> 15:38.170
IT FOLLOWS THE FIRST-EVER
FEDERAL SHORTAGE DECLARATION ON

15:38.237 --> 15:42.241
THE COLORADO RIVER,
TRIGGERING
CUTS TO WATER SUPPLIES IN
THE

15:42.308 --> 15:45.444
SOUTHWEST.

15:45.511 --> 15:49.081
THE COLORADO IS THE LIFEBLOOD OF
THE REGION.

15:49.148 --> 15:52.284
IT WATERS SOME OF THE COUNTRY'S
FASTEST-GROWING CITIES,

15:52.351 --> 15:54.486
NOURISHES SOME OF OUR MOST
FERTILE FIELDS, AND POWERS

15:54.553 --> 15:58.123
$1.4 TRILLION IN ANNUAL ECONOMIC
ACTIVITY.

15:58.190 --> 16:01.527
THE RIVER RUNS MORE THAN
1,400
MILES, FROM HEADWATERS IN

16:01.593 --> 16:06.198
THE ROCKIES TO ITS DELTA IN
NORTHERN MEXICO, WHERE IT
ENDS

16:06.265 --> 16:07.499
IN A TRICKLE.

16:07.566 --> 16:13.505
SEVEN STATES AND 30 NATIVE
AMERICAN TRIBES LIE IN THE

16:13.572 --> 16:14.206
COLORADO RIVER BASIN.

16:14.273 --> 16:19.511
LATELY, THE RIVER HAS BEEN
RUNNING DRY DUE TO THE

16:19.578 --> 16:24.983
HISTORICALLY SEVERE DROUGHT.

16:25.050 --> 16:29.321
THE MAJESTIC, MEANDERING
COLORADO RIVER, THAT CUT THROUGH

16:29.388 --> 16:31.523
THESE RED CLIFFS, CARVING
THE
GRAND CANYON, IS A WONDER OF

16:31.590 --> 16:34.193
NATURE AND HUMAN INGENUITY.

16:34.259 --> 16:38.230
THE GLEN CANYON DAM CREATED
LAKE POWELL AND, 300 MILES

16:38.297 --> 16:44.703
DOWN-RIVER, LAKE MEAD SITS
BEHIND THE HOOVER DAM.

16:44.770 --> 16:46.538
THESE RESERVOIRS ARE NOW
BEING
SUCKED DRY BY 40 MILLION

16:46.605 --> 16:49.508
DIFFERENT STRAWS-- THAT'S
THE
NUMBER OF PEOPLE IN BOOMING

16:49.575 --> 16:53.846
WESTERN STATES WHO DEPEND ON THE
COLORADO TO QUENCH THEIR THIRST,

16:53.912 --> 16:58.183
POWER THEIR HOMES, WATER
LAWNS
AND SPLASH IN THE SUN.

16:58.250 --> 17:01.587
ITS WATERS IRRIGATE FARMS
THAT
PRODUCE 90% OF THE COUNTRY'S

17:01.653 --> 17:05.391
WINTER GREENS.

17:05.457 --> 17:07.693
TO ALL THESE DEMANDS, ADD THE
STRESS OF A 22-YEAR DROUGHT, AS

17:07.760 --> 17:13.265
DRY AS ANY PERIOD IN 1,200
YEARS, AND YOU HAVE A RIVER
IN

17:13.332 --> 17:13.565
CRISIS.

17:13.632 --> 17:17.069
THESE WHITE BATHTUB RINGS; IS--
IS THIS WHERE THE WATER USED TO

17:17.136 --> 17:18.303
BE?

17:18.370 --> 17:19.571
>> Brad Udall: ABSOLUTELY.

17:19.638 --> 17:22.408
>> Whitaker: BRAD UDALL, A
CLIMATE SCIENTIST AT
COLORADO

17:22.474 --> 17:26.245
STATE UNIVERSITY, WENT OUT
ON
LAKE POWELL WITH US.

17:26.311 --> 17:30.149
SO ALL OF THIS WOULD HAVE
BEEN
UNDERWATER?

17:30.215 --> 17:30.516
>> Udall: YEAH.

17:30.582 --> 17:34.253
>> Whitaker: SO WHAT DOES THIS
TELL YOU ABOUT WHAT'S HAPPENING

17:34.319 --> 17:36.622
ON THE COLORADO RIVER?

17:36.688 --> 17:38.290
>> Udall: WELL, IT'S A SIGNAL OF
THE LONG-TERM PROBLEM WE'VE BEEN

17:38.357 --> 17:42.261
SEEING SINCE THE YEAR 2000,
WHICH IS, CLIMATE CHANGE IS

17:42.327 --> 17:46.265
REDUCING THE FLOWS OF THE
COLORADO SIGNIFICANTLY.

17:46.331 --> 17:49.568
>> Whitaker: LAKE POWELL AND
LAKE MEAD, THE TWO BIGGEST

17:49.635 --> 17:54.273
RESERVOIRS IN THE COUNTRY, WERE
NEARLY FULL IN 2000.

17:54.339 --> 17:58.243
TODAY, THEY ARE AT JUST
ABOUT
30% CAPACITY.

17:58.310 --> 18:01.914
>> Udall: THE LAKE'S NOW 155
FEET BELOW FULL.

18:01.980 --> 18:05.050
IT'S DROPPED SOMETHING LIKE
50
FEET THIS YEAR.

18:05.117 --> 18:06.318
>> Whitaker: AND IT'S STILL
DROPPING?

18:06.385 --> 18:07.653
>> Udall: YES.

18:07.719 --> 18:10.322
AND THAT'S WHEN POWER GENERATION
ACTUALLY BECOMES TO COME INTO

18:10.389 --> 18:11.857
QUESTION.

18:11.924 --> 18:13.425
>> Whitaker: SO IT DROPS SO LOW
THAT IT MAY NOT BE ABLE TO

18:13.492 --> 18:14.326
GENERATE--
>> Udall: IT MAY NOT BE ABLE TO

18:14.393 --> 18:15.594
GENERATE POWER.

18:15.661 --> 18:17.629
>> Whitaker: --HYDROELECTRIC
POWER?

18:17.696 --> 18:18.330
>> Udall: YEAH.

18:18.397 --> 18:22.334
>> Whitaker: BRAD UDALL HAS
STRONG CONNECTIONS TO THE RIVER.

18:22.401 --> 18:25.671
AS SECRETARY OF THE INTERIOR,
HIS UNCLE, STEWART UDALL, OPENED

18:25.737 --> 18:29.074
THE GLEN CANYON DAM.

18:29.141 --> 18:31.677
HIS FATHER, CONGRESSMAN MO
UDALL, FOUGHT TO CHANNEL
RIVER

18:31.743 --> 18:34.313
WATER TO ARIZONA.

18:34.379 --> 18:37.683
AS A YOUNG MAN, BRAD WAS A
COLORADO RIVER GUIDE.

18:37.749 --> 18:42.120
TODAY, HE ANALYZES THE IMPACT OF
CLIMATE CHANGE ON WATER

18:42.187 --> 18:42.387
RESOURCES.

18:42.454 --> 18:46.325
IS THE WEST ON A COLLISION
COURSE WITH CLIMATE CHANGE?

18:46.391 --> 18:49.661
>> Udall: IN SOME WAYS, YES, BUT
WE HAVE FULLY UTILIZED THIS

18:49.728 --> 18:50.329
SYSTEM.

18:50.395 --> 18:54.333
WE'VE OVER-ALLOCATED IT, AND WE
NOW NEED TO THINK ABOUT HOW TO

18:54.399 --> 18:57.402
TURN SOME OF THIS BACK.

18:57.469 --> 19:00.072
BECAUSE THE ONLY LEVER WE
CONTROL RIGHT NOW IN THE
RIVER

19:00.138 --> 19:01.006
IS THE DEMAND LEVER.

19:01.073 --> 19:05.377
WE HAVE NO CONTROL OVER THE
SUPPLY.

19:05.444 --> 19:06.411
SO WE HAVE TO DIAL BACK DEMAND.

19:06.478 --> 19:10.382
>> Whitaker: 70% OF COLORADO
RIVER WATER GOES TO AGRICULTURE.

19:10.449 --> 19:16.655
WHEN THE FEDERAL GOVERNMENT
DECLARED THE WATER SHORTAGE, IT

19:16.722 --> 19:17.322
TRIGGERED MANDATORY
CUTBACKS.

19:17.389 --> 19:19.725
PINAL COUNTY, ARIZONA GOT
HIT
HARD.

19:19.791 --> 19:24.263
>> Waylon Wuertz: PINAL COUNTY
ALONE, WE'RE GOING TO BE LOSING

19:24.329 --> 19:26.398
300,000 ACRE FEET OF SURFACE
WATER.

19:26.465 --> 19:31.737
THAT'S WATER THAT WOULD BE
DELIVERED FROM LAKE POWELL,

19:31.803 --> 19:34.406
LAKE MEAD.

19:34.473 --> 19:37.576
AS PART OF THE COLORADO
RIVER.

19:37.643 --> 19:42.381
300,000 ACRE FEET IS 98 BILLION
GALLONS OF WATER.

19:42.447 --> 19:46.118
>> Whitaker: WAYLON WUERTZ FARMS
500 ACRES IN PINAL COUNTY, SOUTH

19:46.184 --> 19:46.418
OF PHOENIX.

19:46.485 --> 19:49.721
HIS FAMILY HAS TILLED SOIL HERE
FOR FOUR GENERATIONS.

19:49.788 --> 19:54.393
IT'S SOME OF THE MOST PRODUCTIVE
LAND IN THE STATE.

19:54.459 --> 20:00.399
CROPS FROM PINAL COUNTY ARE
SHIPPED ALL OVER THE
COUNTRY.

20:00.465 --> 20:06.405
WUERTZ GROWS GOURDS, COTTON, AND
ALFALFA-- PROFITABLE BUT THIRSTY

20:06.471 --> 20:10.409
CROPS-- AND HIS ALLOTMENT OF
COLORADO RIVER WATER IS
BEING

20:10.475 --> 20:12.711
CUT BY 70%.

20:12.778 --> 20:13.745
THIS IS COLORADO RIVER
WATER?

20:13.812 --> 20:17.249
>> Wuertz: YEAH, KIND OF
THE--
THE LIFELINE OF OUR
IRRIGATED

20:17.316 --> 20:18.016
A.G. HERE.

20:18.083 --> 20:19.751
>> Whitaker: THIS COMES STRAIGHT
IN FROM LAKE MEAD?

20:19.818 --> 20:21.219
>> Wuertz: CORRECT.

20:21.286 --> 20:23.956
THIS IS-- THROUGH HUNDREDS
OF
MILES OF CANAL SYSTEM.

20:24.022 --> 20:29.861
IT'S MADE ITS WAY DOWN HERE
TO
CENTRAL ARIZONA.

20:29.928 --> 20:31.730
>> Whitaker: AND WHAT PERCENTAGE
OF YOUR WATER IS SUPPLIED BY

20:31.797 --> 20:34.399
THIS CANAL?

20:34.466 --> 20:37.736
>> Wuertz: IT'S BEEN CLOSE TO
50% OF THE WATER THAT WE'VE USED

20:37.803 --> 20:38.437
TO-- TO FARM HERE.

20:38.503 --> 20:42.374
AND, THIS NEXT YEAR, IT'S
PROBABLY GOING TO DROP DOWN
TO

20:42.441 --> 20:45.243
ABOUT 20% OF THE WATER THAT
WE
USE.

20:45.310 --> 20:46.578
>> Whitaker: THAT'S ONE-SEVENTH
OF WHAT HE WAS GETTING A DECADE

20:46.645 --> 20:49.748
AGO.

20:49.815 --> 20:54.386
TO USE LESS WATER AND MAKE ENDS
MEET, WUERTZ SOLD MORE THAN 300

20:54.453 --> 20:58.390
ACRES TO A SOLAR FARM.

20:58.457 --> 21:02.461
HE DIPPED INTO RETIREMENT FUNDS
TO REPAIR AND RESTART OLD WELLS.

21:02.527 --> 21:06.665
HE LASER-LEVELED HIS FIELDS TO
MAKE IRRIGATION MORE EFFICIENT.

21:06.732 --> 21:09.801
BUT IT'S JUST NOT ENOUGH, IN THE
MIDDLE OF THIS DROUGHT.

21:09.868 --> 21:10.469
>> Wuertz: NO, IT'S NOT ENOUGH.

21:10.535 --> 21:14.473
>> Whitaker: SO NEXT YEAR, HE
TOLD US, HE'LL HAVE TO LEAVE 150

21:14.539 --> 21:17.643
ACRES UNCULTIVATED.

21:17.709 --> 21:19.811
>> Wuertz: WHAT YOU SEE GREEN
HERE IS EVENTUALLY GOING TO DIE.

21:19.878 --> 21:23.415
I HOPE WE'LL HAVE ENOUGH
WATER
TO PLANT IT IN THE FUTURE.

21:23.482 --> 21:25.317
BUT MORE THAN LIKELY, IT'S GOING
TO STAY BROWN FOR QUITE SOME

21:25.384 --> 21:25.817
TIME.

21:25.884 --> 21:29.054
>> Amelia Flores: ALL THE WATER-
USERS ARE GOING TO HAVE TO GIVE

21:29.121 --> 21:31.790
UP SOMETHING TO KEEP THAT WATER
IN THE LAKE.

21:31.857 --> 21:36.795
>> Whitaker: AMELIA FLORES IS
CHAIRWOMAN OF THE COLORADO RIVER

21:36.862 --> 21:41.667
INDIAN TRIBES, A RESERVATION OF
FOUR TRIBES A FEW HOURS WEST OF

21:41.733 --> 21:46.471
PHOENIX, WITH THE OLDEST AND
LARGEST WATER RIGHTS IN ARIZONA.

21:46.538 --> 21:49.808
AFTER BEING MOVED TO
RESERVATIONS, SOUTHWEST
TRIBES

21:49.875 --> 21:54.246
GOT RIGHTS TO ABOUT A QUARTER OF
THE RIVER'S FLOW, BUT GOVERNMENT

21:54.312 --> 21:55.814
RED TAPE AND LACK OF
INFRASTRUCTURE HAVE
PREVENTED

21:55.881 --> 21:58.517
THEM FROM USING THEIR FULL
ALLOTMENT.

21:58.583 --> 22:04.756
FLORES TOLD US, UNTIL THIS
DROUGHT, TRIBES WERE NEVER

22:04.823 --> 22:06.525
INCLUDED IN WATER NEGOTIATIONS.

22:06.591 --> 22:10.529
WHY HAD YOU NOT HAD A SEAT
AT
THE TABLE BEFORE THIS?

22:10.595 --> 22:13.865
>> Flores: BECAUSE THE
TRIBES
HAVE ALWAYS BEEN OVERLOOKED
IN

22:13.932 --> 22:18.537
THE POLICYMAKING, AND-- AND IN--
IN THE LAW OF THE RIVER.

22:18.603 --> 22:19.871
BUT THAT DAY HAS COME TO AN END.

22:19.938 --> 22:24.409
>> Whitaker: WHEN WESTERN STATES
FIRST DIVVIED UP THE COLORADO

22:24.476 --> 22:29.748
RIVER IN 1922, AND LATER, WHEN
THE FEDERAL GOVERNMENT BUILT THE

22:29.815 --> 22:31.883
HOOVER AND GLEN CANYON DAMS, THE
FUTURE SEEMED BOUNDLESS AND

22:31.950 --> 22:34.519
MANAGEABLE.

22:34.586 --> 22:37.355
THROUGH NEGOTIATION AND
COURT
BATTLES, STATES WORKED OUT

22:37.422 --> 22:41.526
AGREEMENTS-- THE LAW OF THE
RIVER-- TO SPLIT THE WATER

22:41.593 --> 22:45.797
EQUALLY BETWEEN UPPER AND LOWER
BASIN STATES.

22:45.864 --> 22:49.868
THE LOWER STATES USE JUST ABOUT
ALL THEIR ALLOTMENT, AND IT'S

22:49.935 --> 22:50.535
FED THEIR TREMENDOUS GROWTH.

22:50.602 --> 22:54.539
THE UPPER STATES HAVE NEVER USED
THEIR FULL SHARE.

22:54.606 --> 22:58.510
NOW, THEY ARE BOOMING, AND SAY
THEY NEED THE WATER THEY'VE BEEN

22:58.577 --> 23:00.612
PROMISED.

23:00.679 --> 23:02.581
I CAN SEE THE BATHTUB RINGS
AROUND HERE TOO.

23:02.647 --> 23:05.517
>> Zach Renstrom: WE'RE
TRYING
TO KEEP EVERY DROP OF WATER
WE

23:05.584 --> 23:07.953
CAN INTO THIS RESERVOIR FOR NEXT
YEAR'S DRINKING WATER.

23:08.019 --> 23:10.589
>> Whitaker: ZACH RENSTROM
MANAGES THE WATER SYSTEM FOR

23:10.655 --> 23:13.925
WASHINGTON COUNTY IN
SOUTHWEST
UTAH.

23:13.992 --> 23:18.230
ST. GEORGE, THE COUNTY SEAT, IS
ONE OF THE FASTEST GROWING METRO

23:18.296 --> 23:18.630
AREAS IN THE U.S.

23:18.697 --> 23:25.437
ITS POPULATION GREW 29% THIS
PAST DECADE.

23:25.504 --> 23:29.875
THE STATE OF UTAH GETS ABOUT
A
QUARTER OF ITS WATER FROM
THE

23:29.941 --> 23:33.645
COLORADO, BUT MOST OF WASHINGTON
COUNTY HAS ONLY ONE SOURCE, THE

23:33.712 --> 23:36.948
VIRGIN RIVER, WHICH FILLS
THIS
RESERVOIR.

23:37.015 --> 23:38.650
>> Renstrom: SO RIGHT NOW, WE'RE
IN THE PROCESS OF IMPLEMENTING

23:38.717 --> 23:42.287
REALLY STRICT CONSERVATION
MEASURES.

23:42.354 --> 23:43.922
AND IF THE CITIES DON'T
ADOPT
THOSE STANDARDS, THEN WE'LL
BE

23:43.989 --> 23:44.723
OUT OF WATER VERY QUICKLY.

23:44.790 --> 23:46.591
>> Whitaker: WHAT IS "VERY
QUICKLY?"

23:46.658 --> 23:49.928
>> Renstrom: WITHIN THE NEXT
FIVE TO TEN YEARS.

23:49.995 --> 23:54.599
>> Whitaker: SO, IN THE MIDST OF
THIS DROUGHT, UTAH IS PROPOSING

23:54.666 --> 23:58.603
TO BUILD A $1 TO $2 BILLION
PIPELINE, ABLE TO BRING 27

23:58.670 --> 24:02.007
BILLION GALLONS OF WATER A YEAR
FROM DWINDLING LAKE POWELL.

24:02.073 --> 24:06.678
UTAH SAYS IT'S ENTITLED TO
THE
WATER BY LAW.

24:06.745 --> 24:10.649
YOU'RE TALKING ABOUT
SIPHONING
OFF WATER FROM A LAKE THAT'S

24:10.715 --> 24:14.653
ALREADY AT A CRITICALLY LOW
LEVEL, TO HELP A CITY GROW
IN

24:14.719 --> 24:18.623
THE DESERT.

24:18.690 --> 24:22.160
>> Renstrom: EVERY STATE ON THE
COLORADO RIVER WAS ALLOTTED SO

24:22.227 --> 24:22.794
MUCH WATER, AND A WATER BUDGET.

24:22.861 --> 24:25.997
AND SO, WITH THEIR WATER BUDGET,
THE STATE OF UTAH HAS DECIDED

24:26.064 --> 24:28.733
THAT IT WANTS TO USE A PORTION
OF ITS WATER HERE IN ST. GEORGE,

24:28.800 --> 24:29.668
UTAH.

24:29.734 --> 24:32.037
>> Whitaker: BUT IT WAS A BUDGET
THAT WAS SET WHEN WATER WAS

24:32.103 --> 24:33.171
PLENTIFUL.

24:33.238 --> 24:34.206
IT ISN'T ANYMORE.

24:34.272 --> 24:34.706
WHAT IS UTAH HOPING FOR?

24:34.773 --> 24:38.009
>> Renstrom: UTAH WANTS THE
RIGHT TO DO WHAT EVERY OTHER

24:38.076 --> 24:38.710
BASIN STATE HAS DONE.

24:38.777 --> 24:42.180
WE WANT TO MAKE SURE THAT WE
HAVE WATER FOR OUR FUTURE, FOR A

24:42.247 --> 24:44.015
HOTTER, DRYER SCENARIO
THAT'S
COMING UP.

24:44.082 --> 24:50.021
>> J.B. Hamby: BUILDING A MULTI-
BILLION DOLLAR PIPELINE TO PUMP

24:50.088 --> 24:52.224
OUT MORE WATER FROM AN
ALREADY
RAPIDLY DECLINING RESERVOIR

24:52.290 --> 24:55.994
SIMPLY DOESN'T MAKE SENSE IN THE
21st CENTURY.

24:56.061 --> 25:02.033
>> Whitaker: J.B. HAMBY IS VICE
PRESIDENT OF THE BOARD THAT RUNS

25:02.100 --> 25:05.003
CALIFORNIA'S IMPERIAL IRRIGATION
DISTRICT, ONE OF THE RICHEST

25:05.070 --> 25:07.239
AGRICULTURAL REGIONS IN THE
COUNTRY, WITH THE SINGLE LARGEST

25:07.305 --> 25:10.475
ALLOCATION OF WATER ON THE
ENTIRE RIVER.

25:10.542 --> 25:13.478
>> Hamby: THERE'S A LOT OF URBAN
GROWTH AND SPRAWL OCCURRING IN

25:13.545 --> 25:14.713
OTHER PARTS OF THE COLORADO
RIVER BASIN THAT'S REALLY
NOT

25:14.779 --> 25:18.049
NECESSARILY SUSTAINABLE.

25:18.116 --> 25:22.721
>> Whitaker: HAMBY SAYS
CALIFORNIA'S IMPERIAL VALLEY

25:22.787 --> 25:26.091
FARMS HAVE CUT WATER USAGE
ALMOST 20% SINCE 2003, BUT

25:26.157 --> 25:30.729
POINTS OUT AS THE POPULATION OF
ST. GEORGE, UTAH GROWS, SO DOES

25:30.795 --> 25:32.097
ITS WATER USE.

25:32.163 --> 25:35.166
>> Hamby: WE NEED TO THINK
AND
RETHINK ABOUT HOW WE GROW,
AND

25:35.233 --> 25:37.469
IF WE GROW AND WHERE WE
GROW.

25:37.535 --> 25:38.770
>> Whitaker: ST. GEORGE WOULD
SAY THAT THEY'RE NOT ASKING FOR

25:38.837 --> 25:42.741
MORE-- THEY'RE ASKING FOR
WHAT
THEY NEED.

25:42.807 --> 25:46.711
>> Hamby: I THINK WHAT WE ALL
NEED TO HAVE IS A REALITY CHECK,

25:46.778 --> 25:50.415
HERE, AND RECOGNIZE THAT WE LIVE
IN AN ERA OF LIMITS RIGHT NOW,

25:50.482 --> 25:52.050
AND THAT'S NOT GOING AWAY
ANYTIME SOON.

25:52.117 --> 25:54.719
IN FACT, IT'S ONLY GOING TO GET
WORSE.

25:54.786 --> 25:58.723
>> Whitaker: A BIG PART OF THE
PROBLEM IS THE LAW OF THE RIVER

25:58.790 --> 26:02.160
ITSELF, A HODGEPODGE OF RULES
AND REGULATIONS PIECED TOGETHER

26:02.227 --> 26:05.463
OVER THE COURSE OF A
CENTURY.

